  "output": "This is a pure-Python async scraper/CLI (fetchers.py, store.py, pipeline.py, filters.py, notify.py, agent.py) — **there's no React/frontend code in this repo**, so I mapped that category to its closest real equivalent (redundant recompute/recomputation on every item, the backend analog of a wasted re-render). Findings below are all things I verified by reading the actual files, not generic advice.\n\n## 1. N+1 query pattern — `Store.diff()` (`store.py:55-74`)\n\nFor every fetched job, this does a separate `SELECT` and then a separate `INSERT`/`UPDATE`, each individually committed-adjacent:\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    if row is None:\n        new.append(job); self._insert(cur, job, now)\n    else:\n        ...\n```\n\nWith multi-thousand-role boards (Amazon/Microsoft/Apple/Google fetchers each cap at 40 pages × ~10-20/page), this is thousands of round trips per run. Fix: batch the lookup and batch the writes.\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    existing = {}\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 500):          # stay under SQLite's ~999 param limit\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 500]\n        q = f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({','.join('?' * len(chunk))})\"\n        existing.update((r[\"key\"], r[\"content_hash\"]) for r in self.conn.execute(q, chunk))\n\n    new, changed, unchanged = [], [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        h = existing.get(job.key)\n        (new if h is None else changed if h != job.content_hash else unchanged).append(job)\n\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n    cur.executemany(_INSERT_SQL, [{**j.to_row(), \"now\": now} for j in new])\n    cur.executemany(_UPDATE_SQL, [{**j.to_row(), \"now\": now} for j in changed])\n    cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=? WHERE key=?\", [(now, j.key) for j in unchanged])\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nAlso add an index for the other hot query path, `added_since()` (`store.py:127-135`), which does `WHERE first_seen > ? ORDER BY first_seen` with only `idx_jobs_company` available — that's a full table scan + sort:\n\n```python\nCREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_jobs_first_seen ON jobs(first_seen);\n```\n\n## 2. Redundant recomputation — `filters.py:11-41` (the \"re-render\" analog)\n\n`_compile()` recompiles every include/exclude regex **for every job**, inside the per-job `match()` call, which itself runs inside a list comprehension over all jobs:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs, rules):\n    ...\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=rules.get(\"include_keywords\"), ...)]\n\ndef match(job, *, include=None, exclude=None, ...):\n    if exclude:\n        if any(p.search(haystack) for p in _compile(exclude)):   # recompiled every call\n```\n\nFor N jobs and K keywords, that's N×K regex compilations instead of K. Fix: compile once outside the loop and pass compiled patterns through.\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    cutoff = _cutoff(rules)\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    locations = [l.lower() for l in rules.get(\"locations\") or []]\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude,\n                                      locations=locations, cutoff=cutoff)]\n\ndef match(job, *, include: list[re.Pattern] = (), exclude: list[re.Pattern] = (),\n          locations: list[str] = (), cutoff=None) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    ...\n```\n\n## 3. Caching opportunity — `Job.content_hash` (`models.py:66-69`)\n\nIt's a plain `@property`, so every access re-hashes, and `diff()` accesses it once for the compare and again inside `to_row()` for insert/update — 2× sha256 per changed/new job per run. Low severity (sha256 of a short string is ~1μs) so I wouldn't add a caching layer just for this — but if you batch `diff()` per fix #1, compute `content_hash` once per job into a local var and reuse it, rather than adding `cached_property` machinery to a `slots=True` dataclass.\n\n## 4. Blocking I/O inside the async pipeline — `notify.py` + `pipeline.py:44`\n\n`run()` is `async def`, but `dispatch()` (`notify.py:105-109`) calls `httpx.post` (sync) and `smtplib.SMTP` (sync/blocking) serially for up to 5 notifiers. Since nothing else runs concurrently at that point in a single CLI invocation this isn't currently costly, but it does mean a slow/hanging SMTP or Slack webhook stalls the whole process sequentially. If you ever add more notifiers or call `run()` from something with concurrent work, switch to `httpx.AsyncClient` + `asyncio.gather`, or wrap the sync calls in `asyncio.to_thread`.\n\n## Memory leaks — none found\n\nThe process is short-lived per invocation, `httpx.AsyncClient` is only closed by whoever created it (`fetchers.py:1129-1146`, `owns_client` guard is correct), and `Store` is used via context manager everywhere except in one place worth a look: `agent.py:62-63`'s `_store()` helper returns a raw `Store` — used correctly via `with _store(...)` in every caller I checked, so no leaked connections currently, just worth keeping an eye on if a new call site forgets the `with`.\n\nOne related note (not a leak, but worth flagging given your saved memory on [parallel worker collisions](jobsquare-parallel-worker-collisions.md)): `Store.__init__` doesn't set `PRAGMA journal_mode=WAL`, so concurrent pipeline workers hitting `next_seq`'s `BEGIN IMMEDIATE` (store.py:111-125) serialize on the default rollback-journal lock rather than WAL's finer-grained locking. Adding `self.conn.execute(\"PRAGMA journal_mode=WAL\")` after connect would reduce contention for that scenario.\n\n---\n\n**Priority order**: #1 (N+1 diff) is the only one with real, measurable impact given board sizes in `sources.yaml` (Amazon/Microsoft/Apple/Google each configured for thousands of roles) — worth fixing. #2 is cheap to fix and meaningfully reduces regex overhead at scale. #3 and #4 are minor; I'd leave them unless you're already touching those files.\n",
